            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"> Advanced Decks</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">Shimmer Superstar v 2.0</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size=1>(4.42)</font> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=22350">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=6010">Andrew "cfbnv" Harwell</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=6010&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Like free energy?  Want a consistent deck?  Like getting the same awesome hand and draws every game by no accident?  Like Shimmer&#39;s picture?  You&#39;ll love this deck.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> March 24, 2002</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Magi:<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(898)">Delia</a><br>
(Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(336)">Vellup</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(356)">Shooting Star</a>)<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(345)">Shimmer</a><br>
(Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(668)">Storm Shield</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(356)">Shooting Star</a>)<br>
<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(528)">Sorreah</a><br>
(Starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(670}<a href="javascript:card_browser({528)">Sorreah</a>&#39;s Dream</a>, Any two Arderial spells)<br>
<br>
Creatures (19):<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(339}<a href="javascript:card_browser({337)">Xyx</a> Minor</a> - 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(337)">Xyx</a> - 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(336)">Vellup</a> - 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(661)">Elder <a href="javascript:card_browser(336)">Vellup</a></a> - 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(520)">Flutter Yup</a> - 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(325)">Ayebaw</a> - 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(524)">Warlum</a> - 2<br>
<br>
Relics (9):<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(351)">Storm Ring</a> - 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(507)">Relic Stalker</a> - 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(530}<a href="javascript:card_browser({324)">Alaban</a> Gloves</a> - 1<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(668)">Storm Shield</a> - 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(531)">Arderian-Guard Wings</a> - 1<br>
<br>
Spells (12):<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(498)">Thunderquake</a> - 1<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(355)">Shockwave</a> - 3<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(357)">Storm Cloud</a> - 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(534)">Tranquility</a> - 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(356)">Shooting Star</a> - 1<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(670}<a href="javascript:card_browser({528)">Sorreah</a>&#39;s Dream</a> - 2<br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(669)">Cataclysm</a> - 1<br>
<br>
Total Cards: 40 + 3 Magi   </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> If you&#39;ve read some of the strategy articles or taken a look at some of the top decks around decktech, you know that the two essential concepts of Magi-Nation are energy advantage and card advantage.  This deck is chock full of ways to accomplish both, and capitalizes on free energy and cheap removal.<br>
<br>
The first part of the strategy will be an explanation of your game plan for all three Magi, the second part of the strategy will be explanations of individual cards, and the third part of the strategy will be a plea for people not to rate the deck poorly <i>just</i> because Shimmer has to go to 0 energy, and I&#39;ll explain why it&#39;s not an issue at all.<br>
<br>
<font color=&quot;blue&quot;><b>Delia:</b></font><br>
99.9% of the time you will want to go second with Delia, because that 6 extra energy is invaluable for the Vellup lady.  However, (see my tournament report) if you know your opponent is playing Kazm or something which really gives you Nightmares by going first, go first.  Unless your opponent flips a Cald magi, just grab the Vellup.  If they are playing Cald, grab the Shooting Star and make the Elder Vellup even bigger.  That said, play a Vellup fetch a Vellup, play a Vellup, fetch a Vellup, play a Vellup, fetch an Elder Vellup, play it, and get whatever you need at that point.  If there is a creature you just have to get rid of, fetch Warlum, who fetches Alaban Gloves.  If you want to go for the beatdown and you have Shooting Star or Sorreah&#39;s Dream in hand, fetch a Xyx Minor.  If you just like shocking the opponent as much as I do, grab a Xyx.<br>
Delia&#39;s lifespan should consist mainly of playing Vellups because she nets on free energy for each one played, but she is by no means limited to Vellups.  The beauty of Delia in the first position is her consistency.  By always starting with a steady chain of creatures that gain free energy, you are accumulating massive card and energy advantage right off the bat.  You will always gain four free energy by using only one card out of your hand; now that&#39;s advantage.  Also, since Elder Vellup always nets you another creature, and Warlum can net you any relic, the only thing you can&#39;t fetch at will are the spells!  However, since you are doing all this fetching and drawing with Delia, by the time Shimmer comes around (if Shimmer comes around) you should be drawing key card after key card.<br>
<br>
<font color=&quot;blue&quot;><b>Shimmer:</b></font><br>
The highly controversial Arderial mistress, many people don&#39;t like her because she &quot;has&quot; to go to 0 energy (again, since my report if you think that&#39;s true).  Let&#39;s look at the downfalls of going to 0 energy: Your opponent plays a mass removal spell and kills you.  Simple right? Wrong!  If you play it right, you are way out of range of any energy discarding spells (Thunderquake, Wildfire, and such) because Storm Shield nets you so much energy!  If you even play four creatures on your way to 0 energy, you get 8 free energy at the end of your turn, which by itself is almost as much as a maximum Thunderquake.  When you take this fact and couple it with Arderian-Guard Wings and Tranquility, you start to see just how hard it would be for the opponent to retaliate.  So what about Ormagon and Cataclysm?  It doesn&#39;t matter how much energy you have for those two, right?  I don&#39;t know if you noticed, but both of those cost 10 energy.  I don&#39;t know too many magi that have energize rates of 10, but I do know that Xyx can keep their magi at no energy by the end of each of your turns.  So if you are playing against Arderial or Underneath or anyone you suspect of having mass removal, keep their magi low on energy and keep your creatures high on energy (<--hehe).  Shimmer can use a lot of the mass removal spells to a great advantage.  Storm Cloud during your second P/R/S step is as good as a Shockwave because of Shimmer&#39;s Effect.  You can Thunderquake and leave all the creatures at 1 only for them to die at end of turn.  If you haven&#39;t tried this deck, it&#39;s hard to understand its true power, but know this:  Playing Shimmer is like setting the timer on a nuclear bomb: every turn you live it gets harder and harder for your opponent to dig their way back to winning since Shimmer gets free energy every turn (and removes energy on top of all that).  If you STILL think Shimmer is risky and not worth it, I give up.<br>
<br>
<font color=&quot;blue&quot;><b>Sorreah:</font></b><br>
To tell you the truth I am really thinking about playing Ora in this slot.  I mean, she nets free energy just like the other two magi, which fits the theme perfectly.  However, I have only played this deck once when someone got past Shimmer, and at that point I was glad to have Sorreah who could grab two Shockwaves and such.  Sorreah is a great finsihing magi because he has so many ways to clean up the board.  By grabbing any two Arderial spells and Sorreah&#39;s dream, Cataclysm + Xyx + Sorreah&#39;s Dream spells instant doom for your opponents third magi.  Also, if you need to play it out against a final magi or whatever, their powers and effects are cancelled, taking away their entire advantage.  As I said, Ora may be better in this slot, but I&#39;ve never been able to test either of their effectiveness because no one can get past Shimmer!<br>
<br>
<font color=&quot;blue&quot;>Why in the heck do I play:</font><br>
<br>
<b>Tranquility:</b><br>
Last time I posted this people didn&#39;t like it, and I did end up taking out one of them, but this card is so good!  It&#39;s two energy casting cost couples well with a Xyx or Warlum when you are keeping Shimmer at 0 energy, it replaces itself by netting you another card, AND it protects Shimmer and the other magi from mass removal like Thunderquakes and Wildfires. (Cald can hurt if you don&#39;t have protection)  Another reason I play Tranquility is as an answer to everyone&#39;s favorite Delia killer: Orothe.  Orothe has Reef Hyren and it has the ever popular O&#39;qua + Deep Hyren.  That&#39;s right, play Tranquility before any creatures and Reef Hyren doesn&#39;t hurt the swarm, and play Tranquility after creatures and prolong the Deep Hyren for a turn.  (More than enough time to kill O&#39;Qua and/or draw a Shockwave).<br>
<br>
<b>A Single Thunderquake:</b><br>
To tell you the truth, I only have one.  If you have another, add it, it&#39;s just that versatile.<br>
<br>
<b>Storm Cloud:</b><br>
I think is card is pretty overlooked and highly underrated, but believe me it is money!  I started out putting it in my deck as answer to the opening Kazms I kept seeing (it&#39;s hard to play a creature with less than one energy ;) ) and by playing it more and more I realized its many powers.  As I said under Shimmer it&#39;s as good as Shockwave since she removes another energy, and playing 5 removal spells in your deck is some good.  Also has a 5 energy cost, making it easy for Shimmer to go to 0.<br>
<br>
<b>Ayebaw:</b><br>
If you compare this deck with the last one you will notice that Ayebaws can in and Xyx Elders came out.  Why?  While I was reviewing a Cald deck I found myself writing for the 80th time that die rolls = inconsistent, and paying 3 for Thermal Blast was not worth it... Then I thought, how in the world is 6 energy for a die roll that could kill half of my creatures even REMOTELY worht it?  What was I thinking!?  Ayebaw, on the other hand, works great in this deck.  It&#39;s 5 energy cost means Shimmer can play it to stay at 0, and it&#39;s ability to attack twice means any free energy it gains (and it gains a lot with Storm Ring and Shield) is put to double duty.<br>
<br>
<b>Alaban Gloves:</b><br>
I&#39;ve heard a lot of criticism about this card, but oohhh noo.. I&#39;d like to thank Ryan Mitchell for implanting the idea in my head that good decks use Gloves, and I decided to give it a test run...  Sure the opposing magi gets the energy back, but I&#39;d always rather attack a magi than attack a creature.  Since I can grab the Gloves with the Vellup/Warlum chain, the possibilities and consistency of the Gloves is just sick.  And oh, with Shimmer...  Shimmer has to go down to 0 energy, but her creatures don&#39;t.. Just energize, Alaban Gloves that 30 energy Xyx Minor who has been accumulating with Storm Shield and its own power and you&#39;re in Thunderquake range all over again.<br>
<br>
<font color=&quot;blue&quot;>Why in the deck don&#39;t I play:</font><br>
<br>
<b>Rayje&#39;s Belt:</b> <br>
For one, I don&#39;t have any, but even if I did I don&#39;t know what I&#39;d take out...<br>
<br>
<b>Beam of Light:</b><br>
It&#39;s four energy cost goes HORRIBlY with Shimmer, and it&#39;s just too expensive in this deck to be worth it.<br>
<br>
So one final plea as promised: No three star reviews that say: Shimmer has to go to 0 energy yadda yadda yadda.  I&#39;ve explained in a thousand different ways why it&#39;s not problem (Xyx, Tranquility, high energy), how you can still get energy (Gloves), and why Shimmer is SO powerful.  Just think about Tryn for all your creatures at the end of every turn, PLUS removing one energy from all your opponents creatures!  This deck is tried, tested, true, and consistent, and for those of you who like to hear numbers it&#39;s 12-0.<br>
<br>
Thanks for reading all this!<br>
~Andrew <br>
